emale":"1246–Deceased","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1180–Male":"1180–Deceased","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","abt 1244":"about 1244","1280":"1280","1180":"1180","1238":"1238","1204":"1204","1246":"1246","1234":"1234","1244":"1244","1200":"1200","1221":"1221","1320":"1320","about 1246":"about 1246","1329":"1329","Isle of Lewis, Ross and Cromarty, Scotland":"Isle of Lewis, Ross-shire, Scotland","Isle Skye, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Scotland","Isle of Lewis, Ross-shire, Scotland":"Isle of Lewis, Ross-shire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Dunvegan Harris, Isle of Skye, Scotland":"Isle of Skye, Inverness-shire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mac","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Cuong, Minh, Lien, Muoi, Thanh, Tho, Tieu, Vinh, Anh, Beo, Binh, Chau.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 麥 (see   Mai   2) and 莫 (see   Mo   1).","Vietnamese (<b>Mạc</b>): from Chinese 莫 ‘nothing; nonexistent’; see   Mo   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Mai","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Thanh, Hoa, Son, Dung, Long, Binh, Minh, Thu, Hue, Huong, Thuy.  Chinese Chi, Hong, Ho, Sang, Han, Hang, Jian, Li, Man, Mei, Sen, Wei.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 麥, meaning ‘wheat’ in Chinese: (i) from Mai Qiu (麥丘), the title of a man in the state of Qi (located mainly in present-day Shandong province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), who, despite being very old, came to celebrate the birthday of the Duke Huan of Qi (ruler of the state of Qi, died 643  BC ). His descendants inherited 麥, the first part of his title, as their surname. (ii) borne by descendants of Mai Tie Zhang (麥鐵杖), a famous general during the Sui dynasty (581–618  AD ). His descendants were scattered around southern China.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 買, meaning ‘buy’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of the king Song Weizi, founder of the state of Song. (ii) borne by descendants of the Duke Dao of Xu (ruler of the state of Xu, 546–523  BC ), possibly inheriting his personal name. (iii) from the first element of the personal name Mai Zhu Chu (買朱鉏), style name of an official who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iv) it has also been traced back to other ethnic groups in northern China."]}]},{"name":"Raild","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Frieda, Gerhard, Hermann.","South German:","Swabian nickname for a nimble person, from a diminutive of Middle High German <i>rē</i> ‘roe deer’."],"variants":[{"name":"Rail","meanings":["English (Cornwall): perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>raile</i> ‘rail, bar, barrier, stake’ (Old French <i>reille</i> ‘bolt, bar, rung’), perhaps denoting a tall, thin man. Alternatively, it may be from Middle English <i>rail</i> ‘garment, robe, clothing, cloth’ (Old English <i>hrægel</i>).","German: altered form of   Raile  ."]},{"name":"Reile","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Irmgard, Otto.","German: variant of   Reil   1."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Nicarmuin Mac Raild was born in 1204, in Isle of Skye, Inverness-shire, Scotland as the daughter of MacCrailt Armuninn Lord of Dunvegan, Durnish, Bracadale and Minginish. She married Leod Olafson 1st Clan Chief Macleod in 1220, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 3 daughters. She died in 1260, in Scotland, at the age of 56, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"1204–1260":"1204–1260","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1221–Male":"1221–Surnud","1234–1329":"1234–1329","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","1246–Female":"1246–Surnud","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","a